Logarithms

Definition: if $y = 2^x$, then $log_2 y = x$.

Logarithms

Example: $1024 = 2^10$, so $log_2 1024 = 10$.

Logarithms (Aside)

Note

In complexity, we generally don’t care about the base, because:

$log_b n = log_x n / log_b x$

$log_b x times log_b n = log_x n$

But $log_b x$ does not depend on $n$ so, given the two bases, it’s a constant.

$C times log_b n = log_x n$

And constants like this do not affect complexity.

Aside

Put these in order (slowest to fastest):
  1. $O(n)$
  2. $O(n!)$
  3. $O(log n)$
  4. $O(1)$
  5. $O(n^3)$
  6. $O(n log n)$
  7. $O(2^n)$
  8. $O(n^2)$

Aside

Put these in order (slowest to fastest):
  1. $O(n!)$
  2. $O(2^n)$
  3. $O(n^3)$ (we call this and the $n$-squared case polynomial)
  4. $O(n^2)$
  5. $O(n log n)$
  6. $O(n)$ (we call this linear)
  7. $O(log n)$
  8. $O(1)$ (constant time, the cost does not depend upon the size of the problem)

Selection Sort

Recall that, on each iteration:

  • we select the smallest element from the unsorted part of the list
  • and swap that element with the one at position $i$

Assertions — Selection Sort

i = 0
while i < len(a):
   p = i                   # find p, the position of the smallest
   j = i + 1               # element in a[i:]
   while j < len(a):       #
      if a[j] < a[p]:      #
         p = j             #
      j = j + 1            #

   tmp = a[p]              # swap a[i] and a[p]
   a[p] = a[i]             #
   a[i] = tmp              #

   #
   #
   i = i + 1

Assertions — Selection Sort

Assertions — Selection Sort

i = 0
while i < len(a):
   p = i                   # find p, the position of the smallest
   j = i + 1               # element in a[i:]
   while j < len(a):       #
      if a[j] < a[p]:      #
         p = j             #
      j = j + 1            #

   tmp = a[p]              # swap a[i] and a[p]
   a[p] = a[i]             #
   a[i] = tmp              #

   assert a[i] <= a[i+1]   # ... or len(a) - 1
   i = i + 1

Assertions — Selection Sort

i = 0
while i < len(a):
   p = i                   # find p, the position of the smallest
   j = i + 1               # element in a[i:]
   while j < len(a):       #
      if a[j] < a[p]:      #
         p = j             #
      j = j + 1            #

   tmp = a[p]              # swap a[i] and a[p]
   a[p] = a[i]             #
   a[i] = tmp              #

   assert i == 0 or a[i-1] <= a[i]
   assert i < len(a) - 1 or a[i] <= a[i+1]
   i = i + 1

Either $p$ is at the end of $a$, or the value at position $p$ is greater than or equal to $q$.

Linear Search (in a Sorted List)

   p = 0
   while p < len(a) and a[p] < q:
      p = p + 1

   assert p == 0 or a[p-1] < q
   assert p == len(a) or q <= a[p]

Exactly one position $p$ in $a$ satisfies both of these properties (always).

Binary Search — Complexity

In general, the problem size roughly halves on each iteration.

Binary Search — Complexity

In general, the problem size roughly halves on each iteration.

So, we consider approximately $log_2(n)$ positions.

Binary Search — Complexity

We consider approximately $log_2(n)$ positions.

So, binary search is $O(log n)$.

And, logarithms grow very slowly as $n$ increases:

  • so this is an efficient algorithm, even for very large lists

E.g. $log_2$ of one billion is a little more than $30$.

Nevertheless, binary search is also:
  • notoriously difficult to get right!

Many professional software engineers (90%?) cannot code binary search correctly.

And, coding binary search is also a classic interview question.

Binary Search — WARNING!

Complications
  • the list may be empty
  • query may not be present
  • query may be present, but with duplicates
    (which one do you want?)
  • query may not be present, and be strictly less than all of the elements
  • query may not be present, and be strictly greater than all of the elements

It is very easy to write a binary search implementation which works for most cases, but is either incorrect or results in an infinite loop for some corner cases.

Binary Search — Implementation

Assume $a$ a sorted list, and $q$ a query

Find the first position $p$ at which $q$ would be positioned in $a$, if $q$ is or were present in $a$.

  • $p$ will be the position after the end of the list

Binary Search — Implementation

Assume $a$ a sorted list, and $q$ a query

Find the first position $p$ at which $q$ would be positioned in $a$, if $q$ is or were present in $a$.

In other words, find position $p$ such that:
assert p == 0 or a[p-1] < q
assert p == len(a) or q <= a[p]

For any $q$ and sorted $a$, exactly one position $p$ satisfies both of these properties.

Our approach:
  • find the midpoint (mid) between low and high
  • then adjust either low or high, depending upon the query $q$ and the value of a[mid]

Binary Search — Implementation

   while low < high:
      mid = (low + high) // 2
      #

The midpoint is just the average of low and high.

Note, however, that this is integer division:

  • if there is a remainder, then it’s rounded down

Binary Search — Implementation

   while low < high:
      mid = (low + high) // 2
      assert low <= mid < high

This is always true.

   low = 0
   high = len(a)

Binary search is:
  • easy to understand
    (it’s like looking up telephone numbers in a phone book)
  • and just a few lines of code

Binary Search

Binary search is:
  • easy to understand
    (it’s like looking up telephone numbers in a phone book)
  • and just a few lines of code
However

There are many many ways to get binary search wrong…

Binary Search — Correct

   low = 0
   high = len(a)

   while low < high:
      mid = (low + high) // 2

      if a[mid] < q:
         low = mid + 1
      else:
         high = mid

   p = low

Binary Search — Wrong

   low = 0
   high = len(a)

   while low < high:
      mid = (low + high) // 2

      if a[mid] < q:
         low = mid           # Infinite loop.
      else:
         high = mid

   p = low

Binary Search — Correct

   low = 0
   high = len(a)

   while low < high:
      mid = (low + high) // 2

      if a[mid] < q:
         low = mid + 1
      else:
         high = mid

   p = low

Binary Search — Wrong

   low = 0
   high = len(a) - 1         # Cannot find position len(a).

   while low <= high:
      mid = (low + high) // 2

      if a[mid] < q:
         low = mid + 1
      else:
         high = mid

   p = low

Binary Search

Stick to this version…

Binary Search — Correct

   low = 0
   high = len(a)

   while low < high:
      mid = (low + high) // 2

      if a[mid] < q:
         low = mid + 1
      else:
         high = mid

   p = low

Binary Search — A Non-Optimisation

   low = 0
   high = len(a)

   while low < high:
      mid = (low + high) // 2

      if a[mid] == q:      # Quit early if we find q.
         low = high = mid  # Yuck!
      else if a[mid] < q:
         low = mid + 1
      else:
         high = mid

   p = low

Possibly incorrect, and not really an optimisation at all.

Binary Search — Correct

   low = 0
   high = len(a)

   while low < high:
      mid = (low + high) // 2

      if a[mid] < q:
         low = mid + 1
      else:
         high = mid

   p = low

Related Problems

The code above can be used to solve a number of related problems too…

  • Is $a$ contained in $a$?
  • At what position is $q$ in $a$?

These solutions will be $O(log n)$ too
